          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In a supine patient with blunt abdominal trauma, where does free intraperitoneal</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In a supine patient with blunt abdominal trauma, where does free intraperitoneal fluid accumulate first?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Pouch of Douglas</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pouch of Douglas (rectouterine pouch) is the deepest recess overall in females, but in the supine position it is not the most dependent point in the right peritoneal cavity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hepatorenal pouch of Morrison</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Morrison's pouch is the deepest recess of the right peritoneal cavity in the supine position. Gravity directs free fluid here first, making it the key site to check on FAST ultrasound in trauma.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lesser sac (omental bursa)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lesser sac is a potential space behind the stomach that communicates with the greater sac only through the narrow epiploic foramen of Winslow. Free fluid rarely enters it first.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Left subphrenic space</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The left subphrenic space lies between the diaphragm and the spleen/stomach. In a supine patient, fluid preferentially collects in the more dependent hepatorenal recess rather than beneath the diaphragm.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In the supine position, Morrison's pouch (hepatorenal recess) is the most dependent peritoneal recess. This is why the FAST scan targets this space first when assessing intra-abdominal haemorrhage."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. Morrison's pouch (hepatorenal recess) is the most gravity-dependent peritoneal recess in a supine patient, making it the first site of fluid collection in abdominal trauma."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
