          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The portal vein forms behind the neck of the pancreas from the union of which two veins?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Superior mesenteric vein and splenic vein</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The portal vein forms at L2 behind the pancreatic neck from the confluence of the superior mesenteric vein (draining the midgut) and the splenic vein (draining the spleen and receiving the inferior mesenteric vein).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Splenic vein and inferior mesenteric vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The inferior mesenteric vein drains into the splenic vein (or the SMV), but it is not one of the two main tributaries that unite to form the portal vein itself.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Left gastric vein and superior mesenteric vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The left gastric vein (coronary vein) drains into the portal vein after it has formed. It is a tributary, not a formative vessel.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hepatic veins and splenic vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The hepatic veins drain the liver into the inferior vena cava, not into the portal system. They carry blood away from the liver, whereas the portal vein brings nutrient-rich blood to it.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The portal vein forms from the union of the superior mesenteric vein and the splenic vein, behind the neck of the pancreas at L2. This confluence is a key surgical landmark."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The SMV and splenic vein unite behind the pancreatic neck at L2 to form the portal vein, which ascends in the hepatoduodenal ligament to supply 75% of the liver's blood."
                }
              ],
