          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During left-sided colorectal surgery, injury to which autonomic plexus causes bladder dysfunction and retrograde ejaculation?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Coeliac plexus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The coeliac plexus surrounds the coeliac trunk at T12–L1, far above the surgical field in colorectal surgery. Its injury would affect foregut function, not bladder or ejaculatory mechanisms.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Aortic plexus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The aortic plexus is a relay station between the coeliac and hypogastric plexuses. While it lies on the aorta, it is the more distal superior hypogastric plexus that is specifically at risk during left-sided pelvic dissection.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Superior hypogastric plexus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The superior hypogastric plexus lies in front of L5 and the aortic bifurcation, directly in the surgical field during left colorectal resection. Its injury disrupts sympathetic fibres to the bladder and genital organs.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Inferior hypogastric plexus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The inferior hypogastric plexus sits on the lateral pelvic walls near the rectum and bladder. While it is at risk in radical hysterectomy and total mesorectal excision, the superior hypogastric plexus is the one specifically endangered during left-sided colorectal surgery.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The superior hypogastric plexus lies anterior to L5 and the aortic bifurcation, placing it directly in the surgical field during left-sided colorectal surgery. Damage causes bladder dysfunction and retrograde ejaculation in men."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The superior hypogastric plexus at L5 is vulnerable during left colorectal dissection. Its sympathetic fibres control bladder neck closure and antegrade ejaculation."
                }
              ],
